# Cross-machine WS backend (mrcall-desktop) — Caddy site config.
#
# desktop.mrcall.ai → the per-profile zylch engines on this VPS. The desktop
# app connects to wss://desktop.mrcall.ai/ws/<uid>; Caddy auto-provisions a
# Let's Encrypt cert (DNS-only A record → this VPS), terminates TLS,
# transparently upgrades the WebSocket, and forwards the
# `Authorization: Bearer <jwt>` header to the engine, which enforces
# `token.uid == OWNER_ID`.
#
# Multi-profile routing: each profile's daemon (zylch-server@<uid>, run by the
# `mrcalld` service user) listens on its own Unix socket /run/mrcalld/<uid>.sock.
# The uid captured from the path selects the socket, so every user shares this
# one URL — no per-user port. A uid with no running daemon → 502 (nothing
# exposed). Security is the per-daemon JWT gate (token.uid == OWNER_ID); a
# mis-route just fails 403, so routing is a hint, not the boundary.
#
# This file is STATIC: adding/removing profiles never changes it (the socket
# path is computed from the uid at request time). See
# docs/execution-plans/multi-profile-routing.md.

desktop.mrcall.ai {
	@ws path_regexp uid ^/ws/([^/]+)$
	reverse_proxy @ws unix//run/mrcalld/{re.uid.1}.sock
}
